Author: floatingtales
Content:
alright so, first of all, what kind of investments/trade do you want to do? There are different options:

- Forex, basically wanting to profit of a change in foreign currency valuation
- Stocks, basically owning a portion of a company, they're gonna give you a cut of the profit every predetermined timespan.
- Treasury/bonds, basically loaning the government some of your money, they're gonna give you interest per month
- Managed Assets, basically giving a company your money to let them manage, stress free, but they take cuts from your profits.
- Crypto, it's forex, but with pretend online money.

I'm sure I missed some, but I can't think of anything right now

Content: For a start I‚Äôd want to do stocks

Author: floatingtales
Content:
so there are different apps for these stuff, I don't dabble in Forex, so idk, but, these are the apps for all of those here.

- Stocks: For US Stocks, gotrade is your best bet. For Indo stocks, there are a couple options, Stockbit, Pintu, Bareksa is one, Bibit is another, or your banking app usually has their own platform.
- Treasury/Bonds: I have some Indonesian bonds, I used Bareksa to buy them
- Managed Assets: Bareksa/Bibit has them
- Crypto: Indodax or Binance

Author: acetyl.ch
Content:
Hello! Idk why I didnt think to post here sooner üòÖ  Sorry for the incoming wall of text üò≥ 

Context: I'm in my early 20s and I've been wanting to really learn more about investing in the indo stock market/learning about finance in the indonesian context in general. I've already invested in reksa dana for the past year or so, so I have maybe an increment of knowledge to begin with... but only with mutual funds LOL. 

So far I've been reading up on some basics, but unfortunately, my b.indo is nowhere near to a level where i would understand local articles/guides on this stuff (more context: i'm a TCK HAHA). Which means I've been trying to find english-friendly guides. The issue is, I'm not sure which information I'm reading is more general and can be applied to any national market, or which might be US-centric/country-specific since it's not always clear.

If anyone would be kind enough to point me to some resources for starters, that'd be swell :D

Author: floatingtales
Content:
I'm just throwing it out there that I'm not a financial guru nor do I have a lot of experience doing financial guru-ing.

I don't know if we do have someone working in stock exchange here, so I can't really say for sure. but there's this thing called "fundamentals" when you're looking at individual stock. these fundamentals usually reflect how good the stock performs over time. The criteria of these fundamentals is the monetary values for this companies: like say, what is their market cap? how much are earnings per share/lot? how much is debt-to-equity? how much is the Net Income? Operating margin? etc.

Now I'm not the guy who can tell you if you give me a figure, is this stock good or not? I just buy whatever a lot of other people recommends, and for indonesian stocks that is banks, with these trackers: BBCA (BCA), BMRI (Mandiri), BBRI (BRI), and also stocks of Gold processing companies like ANTM (Antam) and MDKA (Merdeka Copper/Gold). But I've never gotten as good of a track record as me doing US Stocks.

Content: Let me tell is super simply, what are options

Author: floatingtales
Content: So in options there are 2 things, calls and puts

Author: floatingtales
Content: Calls meaning *to buy* puts meaning *to sell*

Author: floatingtales
Content: Imagine a stock that is valued... Let's say... For the sake of simplicity $100

Author: floatingtales
Content: And you are certain that in the next few hours, price will rise

Author: floatingtales
Content: So you call at $100 (actual price might differ because broker will take a cut too)

Author: floatingtales
Content: If let's say, stock price gets to $110, and the time limit expired/that is your target price, you earn $10

Author: floatingtales
Content:
But if your guess are wrong, and say price dipped to $90

You now lose $10

Author: floatingtales
Content: Now put goes the other way, if you think the stock will go down, you do a put

Author: floatingtales
Content: How this works is that you *borrow* stock and sell it, to rebuy it again at a later time, virtually when stocks are low priced

Author: floatingtales
Content: So let's say current stock price is $100
